<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-569-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 569 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  August 29 1989 v138 pB6(N) pC8(L) 15 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The bargain basement. (shareware and public domain software)(Peripherals)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shannon, L.R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Public domain software and shareware is available for as little as$1.99 per disk.andP;  Shareware is usually low cost software that usersare asked to pay a fee for if they continue to use it.andP;  The feeusually brings written documentation or the right to telephoneassistance.andP;  Public-domain programs are uncopyrighted; they alsocome with no guarantees.andP;  Some programs available for less than$20 are: PC-Write 3.02, PC-Stylist 1.2 and Brother's Keeper, agenealogy program, all from Reasonable Solutions; Edna's Cookbook,Backgammon 2.1, and EGA Arcade Hits from Software Excitement; HomeInventory and Flowcharting 1.20 from MicroStar; and Dot MatrixFonts, San Mateo Education and Wheel of Misfortune from FreewareUnlimited.andP;  Directories for such companies appear in theadvertising sections of computer magazines such as ComputerShopper and PC Magazine.andP;  Users' groups are also a good source.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Reasonable Solutions (marketing)Software Excitement (marketing)Micro Star (marketing)Freeware Unlimited (marketing).andO;Topic:     Public SoftwareMail Order.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>